NOTICE — Source & Attribution
================================

This project (the "academic-paper-writing" Claude Skill) is a derivative,
independently re-written summary of academic-writing best practices.

Original source
---------------
Sacred Heart University Library — "Organizing Academic Research Papers"
(https://library.sacredheart.edu/c.php?g=29803), which is itself based on
materials by Dr. Robert V. Labaree, USC Libraries —
"Organizing Your Social Sciences Research Paper"
(https://libguides.usc.edu/writingguide).

Nature of this work
-------------------
The rules, constraints, and checklists in this repository were distilled and
paraphrased in the authors' own words for instructional/assistant-tooling
purposes. No substantial passages of the original guide were copied verbatim.
The structure (the IMRaD pipeline and section names) reflects widely used,
common academic conventions.

Attribution
-----------
Credit for the underlying educational framework belongs to USC Libraries
(Dr. Robert V. Labaree) and Sacred Heart University Library. This repository
does not claim authorship of that framework, only of the specific wording,
organization, and packaging contained here.

Scope
-----
Only the core paper-writing sections of the original guide were summarized.
Ancillary topics (oral presentations, group projects, book reviews, field
reports, policy memos) and pure-reference pages (glossary, content alerts,
further-readings lists) are intentionally excluded.

Disclaimer
----------
These are general guidelines. A specific assignment's requirements, or a
professor's / journal's instructions, always take precedence. This NOTICE is
informational and is not legal advice. If you intend to redistribute or build
